images.description:
It was pretty discouraging. I wrote a very professional letter. I took 3 pages of items I do company wide, not just my department and condensed it into 5 "highlights". Mentioned reviewing my evaluations and employee feedback. Technically asked for a 6% raise, thinking they would come back with 4% (2% is what we get yearly just for showing up). And without explanation all I got was a "no".

My direct supervisor made it sound like if she does some more work and periodically keeps asking I could probably get 2%. I'm on a subcommittee to help with patient and employee satisfaction with department heads way above my pay grade. They've even admitted that getting a merit raise takes an act of God so I guess I'm not to surprised. 

I owe them nothing, and I'm obviously replaceable. I've had coworkers, managers, and our medical director point out if I left, or stop doing all the things I do, there would be a noticable difference and workflow would suffer. Sure, they could pick up some of the things I do that they see. But there is a lot of behind the scene stuff I do, a lot of attention to detail.

Just venting. I'm just not sure what to do next. I've already committed to discontinuing all the extra stuff I do. If working harder isn't worth compensation, the simple solution is to just not work harder. Thanks for reading, take care, and enjoy your browsing.

Edit: I'm in a small town, 13k, in a rural area. My position is only at two other locations. Place A offered a maximum of a fair amount less, benefits were meh. Place B opening offer was same as Place A, far better benefits, but starting out was part-time, so no actual benefits.

This is the 200 kg (441 lbs) heart of a blue Whale (about 770 times the weight of a human's heart)

It's on display at the Royal Ontario Museum (Toronto) and is the result of an exceptional conservation work done by Jacqueline Miller and her team, after finding a washed up whale in Newfoundland in 2014.

Here's a cool fact for your dirty imgurian mind: during a deep dive, it can conserve oxygen by slowing down to just 2 beats per minute!
